Design a scalable real-time data platform for a global video streaming application similar to:

HBO Max
Netflix
Disney+

The platform must ingest and process user activity events in near real time.

# Functional Requirements

End Users: Business Analytics teams, Monitoring/SRE teams, ML & Recommendation teams, Ad Analytics teams, and Product teams.

Events: playback_start, playback_pause, playback_resume, playback_complete, buffering events, ad impressions/clicks, playback errors, recommendation clicks, and session lifecycle events.
Event Fields: user_id, session_id, device_id, content_id, timestamp, region, app_version, and metadata payload.
Compliance: GDPR and CCPA compliance with PII masking/tokenization, encryption in transit and at rest, RBAC, audit logging, and right-to-delete support.
Pipeline Goal: Real-time analytics, playback issue alerting, ML feature generation, replay/backfill capability, and downstream warehouse/lake ingestion.
Downstream Consumption: SQL queries, BI dashboards, APIs, streaming consumers, feature stores, and warehouse tables.
Ordering Requirement: Ordering required within a user session but not globally.
Delivery Guarantee: At-least-once delivery minimum.
Replay Requirement: Multiple downstream consumers should independently replay events.

---

# Non-Functional Requirements

Latency SLA: Alerts < 5 sec, dashboards < 1 min, ML feature propagation < 5 min.
Retention: Raw events retained for 7 days and aggregated data retained for 1–2 years.
Replay/Backfill: Support replay and reprocessing for up to 7 days.
Traffic Volume: Average 150K–250K events/sec, peak 500K events/sec, and spikes up to 1M events/sec.
Event Size: Approximately 1KB per event before compression.
Scalability: Horizontal scaling required for producers, brokers, and consumers.
Multi-Region: Single-region initially with future multi-region expansion support.
Failure Tolerance: System should tolerate broker/node failures without data loss.
Schema Evolution: Backward-compatible schema evolution required.
Observability: Monitor consumer lag, throughput, latency, broker health, failed events, and DLQ metrics.


# Back-of-the-Envelope Calculations

Kafka Ingestion Rate:

* Peak events = 500K events/sec
* Average event size = 1KB
* Peak throughput ≈ 500 MB/sec

Traffic Spike Handling:

* Expected spike traffic up to 2x
* Spike throughput ≈ 1 GB/sec
* Average sustained throughput assumed ≈ 600 MB/sec

Storage Estimation:
600 MB/sec × 86400 sec/day × 7 days
≈ 350 TB raw storage for 7-day retention

Compression:
Using zstd compression with ~5x compression ratio:
350 TB / 5 ≈ 70 TB effective storage

Serving Layer Estimation:
Assuming 100M active users and ~1KB aggregated serving data per user:
100M × 1KB ≈ 100 GB serving storage

---

# High-Level Design

Client applications (Mobile/Web/TV SDKs) generate playback and engagement events and publish them asynchronously into Kafka.

Kafka acts as the central durable event streaming backbone supporting:

* replayability
* decoupled consumers
* high-throughput ingestion
* multiple downstream consumers

Flink is used for real-time stream processing, including:

* sessionization
* window aggregations
* buffering/error detection
* enrichment
* real-time metrics computation

Processed streams are consumed by multiple downstream systems:

1. S3 Data Lake:
   Raw Kafka events are continuously landed into S3 as the Bronze layer for durable long-term storage and replay support.

2. Snowflake:
   Snowpipe Streaming ingests data from S3/Flink outputs into Snowflake Bronze/Silver/Gold layers for analytical querying and BI workloads.

3. Pinot:
   Pinot stores pre-aggregated low-latency metrics for near real-time dashboards and operational analytics with sub-second to few-second query latency.

4. Redis:
   Redis stores short-lived real-time counters and alerting state for ultra-low-latency operational monitoring and threshold-based alerting.

5. Dashboards:
   Business dashboards are served through Streamlit/PowerBI querying Snowflake and Pinot depending on latency requirements.



1. Kafka over Kinesis/Pulsar

Your answer is GOOD but can be stronger structurally.

Better version:

I would prefer Kafka for this use case because of the very high sustained throughput, replay requirements, ecosystem maturity, and operational flexibility.

Kafka gives finer control over partitioning strategy, retention, consumer scaling, and replay handling. Since multiple downstream consumers independently consume the same event streams, Kafka’s durable distributed log model fits well.

Compared to Kinesis, Kafka is more cloud-agnostic, has a richer ecosystem around Flink/Spark/CDC tooling, and becomes more cost-effective at very large scale. Kinesis also introduces shard limits and AWS vendor lock-in concerns.

Compared to Pulsar, Kafka has a more mature ecosystem, broader operational familiarity, and stronger integration support across stream processing and data platform tooling.

