7. Replay / Backfill

Your answer is actually VERY strong.

This is senior-level thinking.

Only improvement:
Clarify:

Kafka replay
historical lake replay

Because 7 days Kafka retention may not be enough.

Better:

For short-term replay within Kafka retention, I would create a new consumer group and replay directly from Kafka offsets.

For larger historical backfills beyond Kafka retention, replay would happen from the S3 Bronze layer. Updated transformation logic could then reprocess historical data into downstream Silver/Gold layers while ensuring downstream consumers are isolated during replay execution.

This is MUCH stronger.

8. Redis vs Pinot

Your reasoning is GOOD.

But emphasize:

stateful fast thresholding

Better:

Pinot is optimized for analytical querying and operational dashboards, whereas Redis is used for extremely low-latency stateful alerting workflows.

For example, Redis can maintain rolling counters, playback error thresholds, or buffering spikes in memory and trigger near real-time alerts to systems like Datadog or PagerDuty with millisecond latency.

9. Schema Evolution

This answer is GOOD.

Strong improvement:
